One Bible scholar describes the scene this way.

00:21:51.519 --> 00:21:54.519
The worshipper has entered the temple.

00:21:54.519 --> 00:22:00.960
He has passed through its series of courts, the court of the Gentiles, the court of the women,

00:22:00.960 --> 00:22:02.799
the court of the men.

00:22:02.799 --> 00:22:09.319
Beyond that, there lay the court of the priests, into which the laymen could not go.

00:22:09.319 --> 00:22:16.000
The worshipper is standing at the rail, ready to hand over his living animal to the priest.

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:21.279
At that critical moment, the worshipper remembers that his brother has something

00:22:21.319 --> 00:22:24.079
against him.

00:22:24.079 --> 00:22:26.359
What is he to do?

00:22:26.359 --> 00:22:31.519
Leave your gift there in front of the altar, Jesus explains.

00:22:31.519 --> 00:22:34.799
And go away.

00:22:34.799 --> 00:22:39.480
What does Jesus say is more important in offering up a sacrifice?

00:22:39.480 --> 00:22:43.960
First, make peace with your brother.

00:22:43.960 --> 00:22:49.799
Then, when you have come back, offer up your gift.

00:22:49.839 --> 00:22:55.759
The expression rendered make your peace means to reconcile.

00:22:55.759 --> 00:22:59.359
Jesus' words teach a crucial lesson.

00:22:59.359 --> 00:23:04.960
Reconciliation or peace comes before sacrifice.

00:23:04.960 --> 00:23:12.680
The way we treat fellow worshippers has a direct bearing on our relationship with God.

00:23:12.680 --> 00:23:15.799
1 John 4 verse 20 pointedly says,

00:23:15.799 --> 00:23:20.119
For the one who does not love his brother whom he has seen,

00:23:20.119 --> 00:23:24.759
cannot love God whom he has not seen.

00:23:24.759 --> 00:23:29.279
If we find ourselves in a situation when we have offended a fellow worshipper,

00:23:29.279 --> 00:23:31.480
we want to apply Jesus' counsel.

00:23:31.480 --> 00:23:37.039
We want to take the initiative to approach our brother or sister.

00:23:37.039 --> 00:23:40.039
We may need to acknowledge their hurt feelings.

00:23:40.079 --> 00:23:44.640
We may also need to ask, what can I do to make amends?

00:23:44.640 --> 00:23:49.990
Often, a sincere apology is all that is needed.

00:23:49.990 --> 00:23:54.869
Although our worship today no longer includes animal sacrifices,

00:23:54.869 --> 00:24:00.549
what Jesus was teaching emphasizes that there is a connection between

00:24:00.549 --> 00:24:06.109
peace with our brother and acceptable worship to God.

00:24:06.109 --> 00:24:08.549
When two humans are at odds,

00:24:08.589 --> 00:24:11.349
there may be a measure of blame on both sides,

00:24:11.349 --> 00:24:15.230
since both are imperfect and prone to error.

00:24:15.230 --> 00:24:19.150
This usually calls for mutual concessions.

00:24:19.150 --> 00:24:23.150
Even if only the one apologizing is right.

00:24:23.150 --> 00:24:26.670
The issue is not so much who is right and who is wrong,

00:24:26.670 --> 00:24:32.069
but who will take the initiative to make peace.

00:24:32.069 --> 00:24:35.390
When the Apostle Paul heard that the Christians in Corinth

00:24:35.390 --> 00:24:40.869
were taking fellow servants of God to secular courts over personal differences,

00:24:40.869 --> 00:24:46.309
he said, why do you not rather let yourself be wrong?

00:24:46.309 --> 00:24:51.130
But why do you not rather let yourself be defrauded?

00:24:51.130 --> 00:24:53.210
The principle is clear.

00:24:53.210 --> 00:25:01.490
Peace among fellow believers is more important than proving who is right and who is wrong.

00:25:01.490 --> 00:25:06.089
Keeping this in mind makes it easier to apologize for wrong that someone thinks

00:25:06.130 --> 00:25:08.529
we've committed against him or her.

00:25:08.529 --> 00:25:14.089
A heart-felt apology can open the way to a constructive conversation.

00:25:14.089 --> 00:25:20.640
It can minimize problems and restore peace.

00:25:20.640 --> 00:25:24.680
Brother Lynette Myers, a helper to the writing committee,

00:25:24.680 --> 00:25:28.440
will now present the next talk of this symposium.

00:25:28.440 --> 00:25:40.490
Seek peace and pursue it by forgiving freely.

00:25:40.490 --> 00:25:43.609
It's a simple fact that to be at peace with others,

00:25:43.609 --> 00:25:46.890
we must be willing to forgive.

00:25:46.890 --> 00:25:49.410
Please notice two examples.

00:25:49.410 --> 00:25:52.609
A father and his teenage daughter didn't get along.

00:25:52.609 --> 00:25:56.609
Minor disagreements often developed into shouting matches.

00:25:56.609 --> 00:26:02.849
Finally, the tension got so bad that the daughter was asked to leave the house.

00:26:02.849 --> 00:26:08.809
Eventually, she recognized that she was at fault and asked for her father's forgiveness.

00:26:08.809 --> 00:26:13.890
But instead of overlooking her mistakes, her father rejected her efforts.

00:26:13.890 --> 00:26:19.299
He was unwilling to extend forgiveness to his own daughter.

00:26:19.299 --> 00:26:22.660
Now, let's contrast that with another example.

00:26:22.660 --> 00:26:27.779
A blameless man was condemned to die for a crime he didn't commit.

00:26:27.779 --> 00:26:31.740
Shortly before he died, the innocent man stated,

00:26:31.740 --> 00:26:37.339
father forgive them, for they do not know what they are doing.

00:26:37.380 --> 00:26:41.859
Those words of Jesus are recorded at Luke chapter 23 verse 34.

00:26:41.859 --> 00:26:47.099
And he may have been referring to the Roman soldiers who drove the nails into his hands and feet

00:26:47.099 --> 00:26:50.180
and who didn't know who he really was.

00:26:50.180 --> 00:26:54.740
Or Jesus may have had in mind some in the crowd who demanded his execution

00:26:54.740 --> 00:26:57.740
but would later exercise faith in him.

00:26:57.740 --> 00:27:04.119
The point is that Jesus was willing to forgive freely.

00:27:04.119 --> 00:27:07.839
How do we measure up with regard to forgiveness?

00:27:07.839 --> 00:27:12.000
Are we like Jesus willing to forgive others freely?

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:18.859
Or at times do we tend to be more like the man who was unwilling to forgive?

00:27:18.859 --> 00:27:21.500
Granting forgiveness isn't always easy.

00:27:21.500 --> 00:27:27.859
Imperfection exerts a powerful influence over us, sometimes robbing us of compassion.

00:27:27.859 --> 00:27:33.460
When someone hurts us, we may become resentful or hold a grudge.

00:27:33.460 --> 00:27:38.460
And perhaps some of us were taught not to forgive others.

00:27:38.500 --> 00:27:44.019
Little wonder that cultivating a peaceful forgiving spirit can be difficult.

00:27:44.019 --> 00:27:50.539
Still, the Bible encourages us to forgive freely.

00:27:50.539 --> 00:27:54.779
Let's consider another example of forgiveness in the man Job.

00:27:54.779 --> 00:27:59.220
And we're familiar with his trials, loss of his possessions and ten children,

00:27:59.220 --> 00:28:04.420
a loathsome disease, and his wife told him to curse God and die.

00:28:04.420 --> 00:28:10.019
Three companions heard about Job's calamities and they agreed to go comfort him.

00:28:10.059 --> 00:28:13.460
Job chapter 2 verse 13 states that when they arrived,

00:28:13.460 --> 00:28:19.380
they sat with him for seven days and seven nights, but they didn't say a word to him.

00:28:19.380 --> 00:28:23.460
Now maybe that was a good thing, because when they finally opened their mouths,

00:28:23.460 --> 00:28:28.700
they deeply hurt Job with their baseless accusations.

00:28:28.700 --> 00:28:30.940
But notice something interesting about this account.

00:28:30.940 --> 00:28:34.980
Please turn with me to Job chapter 42.

00:28:34.980 --> 00:28:39.460
At the end of Job's trials, Jehovah asked Job to do something regarding these false

00:28:39.500 --> 00:28:40.980
accusers.

00:28:40.980 --> 00:28:47.700
Notice Jehovah's words there, Job 42, the B portion of verse 8.

00:28:47.700 --> 00:28:51.259
And my servant Job will pray for you.

00:28:51.259 --> 00:28:57.700
I will surely accept his request not to deal with you according to your foolishness.

00:28:57.700 --> 00:28:59.140
Did you notice?

00:28:59.140 --> 00:29:01.539
After all the false accusations,

00:29:01.539 --> 00:29:06.059
Jehovah asked Job to pray for the men who had tormented him.

00:29:06.059 --> 00:29:08.460
Now, would Job tell Jehovah?

00:29:08.460 --> 00:29:10.779
Jehovah, after what they said to me,

00:29:10.819 --> 00:29:13.220
I'm not going to forgive them.

00:29:13.220 --> 00:29:16.059
Would Job be resentful?

00:29:16.059 --> 00:29:20.099
Notice the latter portion of verse 9.

00:29:20.099 --> 00:29:24.299
And Jehovah accepted Job's prayer.

00:29:24.299 --> 00:29:27.500
Job followed Jehovah's instructions.

00:29:27.500 --> 00:29:32.380
What was the result of Job's integrity and his forgiving spirit?

00:29:32.380 --> 00:29:34.420
Verse 10.

00:29:34.420 --> 00:29:37.740
After Job had prayed for his companions,

00:29:37.740 --> 00:29:41.740
Jehovah removed Job's tribulation and restored his prosperity.

00:29:41.740 --> 00:29:45.579
Jehovah gave him double what he had before.

00:29:45.579 --> 00:29:48.859
The account goes on to say that Job had 10 more children.

00:29:48.859 --> 00:29:54.059
He lived for 140 more years and for 17 states.

00:29:54.059 --> 00:29:59.019
Finally, Job died after a long and satisfying life.

00:29:59.019 --> 00:30:01.660
Job was blessed for his forgiving spirit.

00:30:01.660 --> 00:30:07.180
And he set a good example for us to forgive freely.

00:30:07.180 --> 00:30:10.140
In the following dramatization with Celia and Haley,

00:30:10.140 --> 00:30:42.019
notice why Haley finally decides to forgive freely.

00:30:42.019 --> 00:30:46.519
Been thinking of you, right, broadcast?

00:30:46.519 --> 00:30:48.359
How did you like the neurovigil?

00:30:48.359 --> 00:30:49.160
I'm sorry.

00:30:49.160 --> 00:30:50.359
Yes, I can't.

00:30:50.359 --> 00:31:08.539
I'm sorry.

00:31:08.539 --> 00:31:09.019
I'm sorry.

00:31:09.019 --> 00:31:12.940
Yeah, I wish you could give her a rest.

00:31:12.940 --> 00:31:13.740
Sorry?

00:31:13.740 --> 00:31:16.980
Oh, nothing.

00:31:16.980 --> 00:31:17.940
I'm sorry.

00:31:17.940 --> 00:31:20.740
It's just Emily for the millionth time.

00:31:20.740 --> 00:31:22.420
What's the problem, love?

00:31:22.420 --> 00:31:24.420
There's no problem.

00:31:25.380 --> 00:31:32.359
It's just difficult to let her back in.

00:31:32.359 --> 00:31:49.940
Not that simple.

00:31:49.940 --> 00:31:53.740
Not that simple.

00:31:53.740 --> 00:32:02.710
You want to forgive, but I'll get burned again.

00:32:02.710 --> 00:32:08.309
Keep in mind, a chance to forgive is a chance to imitate

00:32:08.309 --> 00:32:10.230
Jehovah.

00:32:10.230 --> 00:32:15.500
We wouldn't want to miss that opportunity.

00:32:15.500 --> 00:32:18.779
I never thought about it like that.

00:32:18.859 --> 00:32:26.410
Think back to a time when you wanted forgiveness,

00:32:26.410 --> 00:32:30.170
when it meant everything.

00:32:30.170 --> 00:32:31.369
How did it feel?

00:32:31.369 --> 00:32:38.329
Just like, you feel awful.

00:32:38.329 --> 00:32:40.170
That you've let everyone down.

00:32:40.170 --> 00:32:55.240
They forgive you.

00:32:55.240 --> 00:33:07.750
Suddenly everything's okay.

00:33:07.750 --> 00:33:11.960
Emily, sorry, I haven't been back to you.

00:33:11.960 --> 00:33:18.779
Plans for tomorrow.

00:33:18.779 --> 00:33:21.819
What good reasoning on the part of Celia?

00:33:21.819 --> 00:33:26.059
Did you notice the expression that really touched Haley's heart?

00:33:26.059 --> 00:33:30.220
A chance to forgive is a chance to imitate Jehovah.

00:33:30.220 --> 00:33:33.740
We wouldn't want to miss that opportunity.

00:33:33.740 --> 00:33:37.180
So when we've been wronged, we don't want to miss the opportunity

00:33:37.180 --> 00:33:41.420
to imitate Jehovah by forgiving freely.

00:33:41.420 --> 00:33:46.700
Please notice how this is highlighted at Colossians chapter 3 verse 13.

00:33:46.700 --> 00:33:50.619
When we consider Job's example, remember that Jehovah instructed him to pray for

00:33:50.619 --> 00:33:55.180
his companions, and that helped Job display a forgiving spirit.

00:33:55.180 --> 00:33:57.660
Well, notice here what Jehovah instructs us to do.

00:33:57.660 --> 00:34:00.890
Colossians 3 13.

00:34:00.890 --> 00:34:03.130
Continue putting up with one another

00:34:03.130 --> 00:34:06.329
and forgiving one another freely,

00:34:06.329 --> 00:34:10.250
even if anyone has a cause for a complaint against another.

00:34:10.250 --> 00:34:17.829
Just as Jehovah freely forgave you, you must also do the same.

00:34:17.829 --> 00:34:20.789
The Greek verb used here for freely forgive

00:34:20.789 --> 00:34:26.230
is related to a word often rendered undeserved kindness or favor.

00:34:26.309 --> 00:34:30.949
When used in the sense of forgiving, this verb conveys the idea of doing so

00:34:30.949 --> 00:34:38.949
freely, generously. Just as when you, out of generosity, give a gift to someone.

00:34:38.949 --> 00:34:43.909
Jehovah requires that we freely forgive others in imitation of him.

00:34:43.909 --> 00:34:50.389
Did you notice the end of the verse? You must also do the same.

00:34:50.389 --> 00:34:54.389
Now, if the offense is minor, it's best to overlook it.

00:34:54.469 --> 00:35:00.550
1 Corinthians 13 verse 5 states that love does not keep account of the injury,

00:35:00.550 --> 00:35:07.829
and Proverbs 19 verse 11 tells us that it is beauty to overlook an offense.

00:35:07.829 --> 00:35:12.150
However, if we feel that we need to talk to our brother or sister about an offense that was

00:35:12.150 --> 00:35:16.469
committed against us, what's the best way to handle that?

00:35:16.469 --> 00:35:20.710
First, we should ask Jehovah in prayer for his guidance.

00:35:20.710 --> 00:35:23.829
Then, with the brother's good qualities in mind,

00:35:23.829 --> 00:35:27.110
graciously tell him that we want to make peace.

00:35:27.110 --> 00:35:30.630
Listen carefully and empathetically.

00:35:30.630 --> 00:35:35.349
We shouldn't interrupt, even if we don't agree with everything being said.

00:35:35.349 --> 00:35:41.110
It may be that his viewpoint is wrong, but it is his viewpoint.

00:35:41.110 --> 00:35:45.269
Then, when it's our turn to speak, we want to be gracious.

00:35:45.269 --> 00:35:47.989
Tell the brother what we appreciate about him.

00:35:47.989 --> 00:35:52.869
Apologize for any part that we played in the misunderstanding.

00:35:52.949 --> 00:35:57.269
If our humble efforts result in good, thank Jehovah.

00:35:57.269 --> 00:36:01.670
If they don't, keep asking Jehovah for guidance while we look for another

00:36:01.670 --> 00:36:07.349
opportunity to make peace. When we truly forgive,

00:36:07.349 --> 00:36:10.869
we make a heartfelt decision to let go of resentment,

00:36:10.869 --> 00:36:16.309
and what peace that can bring us. Now, forgiving doesn't mean that we approve

00:36:16.309 --> 00:36:21.750
of a wrong action, consider it unimportant, or pretend it didn't happen.

00:36:21.750 --> 00:36:25.989
Also, if we've been treated unjustly and have a cause for complaint,

00:36:25.989 --> 00:36:29.429
we do what we can to pursue peace and resolve the matter,

00:36:29.429 --> 00:36:34.539
and then we confidently leave it in Jehovah's hands.

00:36:34.539 --> 00:36:38.460
Brothers and sisters, what will you take away from this consideration?

00:36:38.460 --> 00:36:43.340
I'm sure you'll agree that it can be a challenge at times to forgive.

00:36:43.340 --> 00:36:47.179
But rather than be like the man we spoke of earlier who refused to forgive his

00:36:47.179 --> 00:36:51.579
own daughter, may we follow the examples of Jehovah,

00:36:51.579 --> 00:36:55.500
Jesus, Job, and Haley, by forgiving freely,

00:36:55.500 --> 00:37:00.219
generously. Remember, a chance to forgive

00:37:00.219 --> 00:37:06.059
is a chance to imitate Jehovah, and we wouldn't want to miss that opportunity.

00:37:06.059 --> 00:37:13.510
May all of us pursue peace by being willing to forgive freely.

00:37:13.510 --> 00:37:17.190
For the Garrett Loche, a member of the governing body will now present the final

00:37:17.190 --> 00:37:21.110
talk of this symposium. Seek peace and pursue it

00:37:21.110 --> 00:37:32.440
by using our gift of speech wisely.

00:37:32.440 --> 00:37:37.880
Why is it challenging to use our gift of speech wisely?

00:37:37.880 --> 00:37:42.280
Because something powerful constantly works against us.

00:37:42.280 --> 00:37:46.440
What is it? Imperfection.

00:37:46.440 --> 00:37:51.880
The tongue is powerful. It can do much good, but because of imperfection,

00:37:51.880 --> 00:37:55.639
it can also cause much harm.

00:37:55.639 --> 00:38:00.440
This thought is well expressed in the Bible book of Proverbs.

00:38:00.440 --> 00:38:05.079
For example, Proverbs 12, 18 says,

00:38:05.079 --> 00:38:09.800
Thoughtless speech is like the stabs of sword,

00:38:09.800 --> 00:38:14.519
but the tongue of the wise is healing.

00:38:14.519 --> 00:38:21.960
In Proverbs 18, 21 states, death and life are in the power of the tongue.

00:38:21.960 --> 00:38:27.960
Those who love to use it will eat its fruitage.

00:38:27.960 --> 00:38:33.960
Words have power, so we need to be careful about what we say

00:38:33.960 --> 00:38:39.880
and how we say it. Perhaps you can recall when someone spoke

00:38:39.880 --> 00:38:43.960
unkindly to you and hurt you deeply.

00:38:43.960 --> 00:38:51.400
On the other hand, thoughtful speech can mend an aching heart and heal friendships.

00:38:51.400 --> 00:38:56.840
Because of imperfection, we all have difficulty controlling our tongue.

00:38:56.840 --> 00:39:02.360
This was true even of the first century disciple James.

00:39:02.360 --> 00:39:06.760
He humbly acknowledged the challenge that all humans face

00:39:06.760 --> 00:39:11.000
in the third chapter of his inspired letter.

00:39:11.000 --> 00:39:15.480
Notice how James described this in James chapter 3

00:39:15.480 --> 00:39:20.300
verses 3 to 6 and verse 8.

00:39:20.380 --> 00:39:25.900
If we put bridles in the mouth of horses to make them obey us,

00:39:25.900 --> 00:39:31.260
we guide also their whole body. Look also at chips.

00:39:31.260 --> 00:39:35.900
Although they are so big and are driven by strong winds,

00:39:35.900 --> 00:39:41.820
they are steered by a very small rudder wherever the man at the helm is

00:39:41.820 --> 00:39:47.980
inclined to go. So too, the tongue is a small part of the body

00:39:47.980 --> 00:39:54.539
and yet it makes great brags. See how small a fire it takes to set a great

00:39:54.539 --> 00:39:59.340
forest ablaze? The tongue is also a fire.

00:39:59.340 --> 00:40:04.300
The tongue represents a world of unrighteousness among our body members.

00:40:04.300 --> 00:40:09.739
For it defiles all the body and sets the whole course of life on fire

00:40:09.739 --> 00:40:13.900
and it is set on fire by Gehenna.

00:40:13.980 --> 00:40:18.460
And verse 8, but no human can tame the tongue.

00:40:18.460 --> 00:40:24.139
It is unruly and injurious, full of deadly poison.

00:40:24.139 --> 00:40:30.860
In addition to inherited imperfection, our upbringing could also be a factor.

00:40:30.860 --> 00:40:40.300
The watchtower of September 15, 2006, page 21, paragraph 6 states,

00:40:40.380 --> 00:40:47.739
In addition to human imperfection, family environment plays a role in the misuse of the tongue.

00:40:48.699 --> 00:40:53.179
Some people were raised in homes where parents were not open to any agreement,

00:40:53.900 --> 00:41:00.519
without self-control, fears. Despite such challenges,

00:41:00.519 --> 00:41:05.079
it is possible for each one of us to seek peace and pursue it.

00:41:07.260 --> 00:41:14.780
Jesus set a good example in using the gift of speech wisely. He used his speech to encourage

00:41:14.780 --> 00:41:20.699
and comfort others. While on earth he applied to himself the words

00:41:20.699 --> 00:41:25.980
founded Isaiah chapter 61, verse 1, which states the following,

00:41:28.340 --> 00:41:32.820
The spirit of the sovereign Lord Jehovah is upon me, because Jehovah

00:41:32.900 --> 00:41:39.940
anointed me to declare good news to the meek. He sent me to bind up the broken hearted,

00:41:39.940 --> 00:41:45.940
to proclaim liberty to the captives, and the wide opening of the eyes to the prisoners.

00:41:47.300 --> 00:41:54.980
As recorded at Matthew 12 verse 20, Matthew applies the words of Isaiah 42, 1 to 3,

00:41:55.059 --> 00:41:59.300
to Jesus. In Matthew 12 20 he stated,

00:42:00.739 --> 00:42:06.739
No bruised read will he crush, and no smoldering wick will he extinguish,

00:42:06.739 --> 00:42:15.059
until he brings justice with success. We learn an important lesson from such verses,

00:42:15.059 --> 00:42:21.300
Jesus recognized that the tongue has power, power to harm, and power to heal.

00:42:22.260 --> 00:42:31.139
The watchtower of February 15, 2015, page 13, and paragraph 11,

00:42:31.139 --> 00:42:37.780
thus stated that, quote, Jesus showed discernment in all he said and did.

00:42:37.780 --> 00:42:48.469
Can we imitate Jesus more closely? If so, what will you do the next time an opportunity arises

00:42:48.550 --> 00:42:55.190
for you to use your gift of speech wisely? In the following dramatization,

00:42:55.190 --> 00:42:59.349
notice how the wise use of the tongue helps to heal.

